Instructions
Clone the starter code in the link below

https://gitlab.com/cit_4640/intro-to-ansible-lab-files.git

Create a new SSH key pair
- name the new key pair "aws" and add it to your ~/.ssh directory
- use the included "import_lab_key" script to add the new public key to your AWS account.

After importing the public key, run the included terraform configuration. You don't need to edit this. This will create 2 ec2 instances, and output the public ip address and dns name for each.

Use either the ip address or the dns name to complete the hosts.yml file in the ansible/inventory directory. This will create your static inventory of managed nodes.

Use the fully qualified name(FQCN) for all of the modules you use in your playbook.

Complete the "playbook.yml" file so your playbook will:
- install nginx on both servers with the package module
- Create directory for index.html file using the file module
- See nginx.conf file in ansible/files for directory structure
- copy the nginx.conf file to your servers with the copy module
- copy file to /etc/nginx/sites-available/default
- make a link with the file module to /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/default
- create an index.html file from the index.html.j2 template using the template module
- See nginx.conf for where to put index.html file
- reload the nginx service with the service module.
- The default for nginx in Ubuntu is that the service is enabled when you install the package, but just to be on the safe side, make sure the nginx service is enabled too. This is all one task, reload and enable.

Deliverables:

Submit a link to a public git repository that contains the following:
- A README.md file that contains:
- required command(s) to:
- create new keys
- run included scripts to import and delete keys
- terraform commands (init, fmt, validate, plan and apply)
- ansible commands (syntax check, run playbook)
- Put commands in code blocks and include a brief description of each command.
- A screenshot of the rendered html page from one of your servers, they should be almost the same, so just a screenshot of one is fine.
- The ansible directory that contains:
- ansible.cfg
- inventory/hosts.yml
- files/nginx.conf
- templates/index.html.j2
- playbook.yml

You don't need to submit the scripts, or terraform configuration.

Before destroying your infrastructure, demo that you can visit one of your servers in the browser.

Cleanup:

remember to run Terraform destroy when you are done.

You can remove the ssh key with the included "delete_lsb_key" script.
